# Session Bootstrap

Every new session is a fresh onboarding. Do not rely on conversational memory.

## Step 1 — Read AI rules (required)

Before any implementation, read these files in order:

1. `.ai/rules/context-management.md`
2. `.ai/rules/development-workflow.md`

## Step 2 — Read program context (required)

3. `plan.md` — product scope, roles, milestones
4. `progress.md` — current milestone status (Completed / In Progress / Pending)

## Step 3 — Read feature context (when applicable)

If working on a feature, read only that feature's folder under `features/<feature>/`:

- `plan.md`
- `developmentplan.md`
- `progress.md`
- `memory.md`

## Step 4 — Read knowledge layer (on demand only)

Read `knowledge/*` files only when relevant to the current task. Skip empty or unrelated files.

Relevant examples:

- `knowledge/coding-standards.md` — when writing code
- `knowledge/api-standards.md` — when building APIs
- `knowledge/architecture-decisions.md` — when making design choices
- `knowledge/domain-rules.md` — when modeling family tree logic

## Context budget

Use at most ~70% of context for onboarding. Defer deep reads until the task requires them.

## Before implementing

- Explain understanding and assumptions
- Identify the active milestone from `progress.md`
- Only one milestone should be In Progress at a time

## Before ending a session

- Update `progress.md` (move milestones between sections)
- Update feature `progress.md` and `memory.md` if applicable
- Update relevant `knowledge/*` docs if standards or architecture changed

